      text = "                          \
    \"This world is Rotten. Rotten people should be killed off to cleanse this world.\" – Light Yagami\
Ever wondered what’s it’s like to possess the power to eliminate any person you want in the world, with just a pen and a notebook? Those that cause pain and suffering to the world find themselves to be in a very vulnerable position in this dark and twisted show. This review may contain spoilers so please beware!\
Story\
The story of Death Note centres around high school student Light Yagami. He perceives the world to be corrupt and unfixable in its current state, with crime and murder ruining the place where\
          \
        we live. He wants these factors to be eradicated from the world, in order to make it a better place for humans to live. But how can an innocent 17 year old boy possibly do this? With the help of a trusty Death Note of course. Very early into the first episode, Light comes across this menacing notebook, and is perplexed as to what it is. He takes it home with him only to find out that it has the power to kill anyone he wishes, with just the simple task of writing their name in the notebook. Light vows to use this notebook to serve justice upon the crime of the world by deconstructing, and reconstructing his own world where he is the ruler. The story for the most part is very intriguing and is successful in creating an ominous atmosphere for the audience to encounter. It’s not as simple as research and write every name that has a history of crime in the notebook. Light engages in several challenging problems across his experience with the notebook. For one he must deal with the force of the police, and investigator L who attempts to uncover who the person committing all these murders is. This is an effective way of progressing the narrative because it allows the watcher to experience Light’s intelligence, and how he will use this as an advantage to outsmart the opposing side. He may even have to compromise because a plan that he had been preparing for a lengthy amount of time was  breached by a very small problem, but in fact will affect many key things later on if the plan was kept as the original. This means that Light has to be a very quick thinker if he does not want his ultimate secret to be revealed and therefore his downfall. There are numerous unpredictable turns of events throughout the 37 episode span of the series, that will leave the audience to ponder their thoughts as to what came about Light to attempt something so risky yet sinister. The writing of the story has been used in an effective way of portraying Light as a very heinous character. Though it’s general to hate such things, having Light as this paragon of evil sets the tone very well for what the show is trying to be. For the most part, the story was very consistent in quality throughout the show. Though many argue and say that past around episode 26, the quality dips down a bit, it’s not a significant amount to make the overall quality of the plot and narrative bad. Many aspects of Death Note’s writing is taken through cognitive manners also. The anime kindly presents several of Light’s intentions through inner thoughts and monologues to create a sense of foreshadow and an intense vibe to the show. You will surely be amazed as you watch episode by episode how Light chooses to approach certain obstacles with treacherous yet genius decisions which can allow you to question his moral standing in society as he continues to serve ‘justice’ to those who oppose him. Story – 8/10\
Characters\
Moving on to the characters, I will be speaking of the two most significant in my opinion, Light and L. I will also be giving a brief overview of the side characters and their significance. \
Light\
Light is a 17 year old high school student with a thirst for vengeance. He is usually quite isolated and always thinks to himself, though this is able to play a big role in his characterisation once paired with the Death Note. He is very deceptive, and will even go to the extent of sacrificing his own family in order to cover his case regarding the sudden murders, if one were to find out. Having the main character as a debatable antagonist allows the audience to understand Light’s ideals and what makes him commit the actions that he does throughout the show. His sense of morality is not one to take lightly, and one can argue that this notebook being bestowed upon him was the source of this slow deprivation of his once known innocence as he turns into this savage monster with no consideration of others but himself; exerted with pride if you will. Light does develop quite a significant amount throughout the show, as his own ideals soon come back to oppose against him. These contradicting ideas of Light’s characterisation allow the audience to judge whether or not they are rooting for Light, or going against his so called ‘justice’. Whichever way you perceive him, he is a very diverse and detailed character and fits the role he plays well. If I were to criticise his actions slightly, I would say that he sometimes polarises his first intentions. For example, he states that he wants to protect humanity from the horrors of crime and murder, yet his sometimes kills innocent civilians throughout the show, just to protect his case from being uncovered. Though this is not too aggravating for some, it could be taken into account as a flaw. \
L\
L's dishevelled and languid appearance is a clear shroud of his great powers of deduction and insight. He tends to second-guess everything he is presented with, and is very meticulous and analytical with what he does. He is the direct antithesis of Light, with the sole purpose in the anime being to stop the crimes ‘Kira’ (Light) has committed.  I couldn’t say that L possesses higher intelligence than Light, but rather they are balanced in intellect, but both perform actions that outsmart the other on numerous occasions. He sets himself to be quite at ease with most situations, but also well aware of the context and matters that must be addressed. His communications with Light are both humorous and though-provoking. Both are trying to outsmart the other whilst attempting to befriend one another, as L possesses suspicions of Light being the culprit, which the audience knows he is but Light is able to prevent L from uncovering his secret in many ways. This creates dramatic irony as the audience is able to possess more knowledge of Light than L himself has. The relationship between each other possesses numerous psychological traits, as they both have different opinions on the other, than what is really stated in speech between them. The writing allows L to be an extremely likable character, and his contrasting ideals against Light allowed the audience to choose who they will side with. L is both captivating, but menacing as you are unaware of his future actions to deal with the crimes he must solve.\
Side Characters\
Death Note possesses many side characters that contribute to the main plot of the story. These range from Misa, a so-called second ‘Kira’ that adds an additional element of mystery to the plot, to Light’s father Soichiro who is the leader of the investigation team under L’s command and has yet to realise that he is opposing his own son. There are also numerous appearances of supernatural 'death gods' throughout the show, who only appear to those that possess a Death Note. These gods aid in foreshadowing the effects and consequences of using a Death Note, and this helps to create a sense of danger and pre-eminence that over-ride the story. Though characters like these are not shown as much as Light and L, they still are very fundamental to add depth and variety to both the plot and characters we see over the course of the show. Characters – 9/10\
Art & Animation\
The art to Death Note can be described as being ‘morally grey’. The dark overtones that are blended into both the background and the foreground give justice to the tone of the show. This is because it adds to the atmosphere that Death Note creates with its plot and characters, and allows the audience to further appreciate the situations due to the colour pallet chosen. Character designs can said to be generic, however aid in the characterisation of said character. The animation of the show isn’t really something special; however it doesn’t need to be. The animation could be plain dark and shady, and it would work because of the atmosphere the show puts itself in. Psychological thrillers tend to have a similar colour choice to each other, as they all attempt to present the same kind of atmosphere and genre. Art & Animation – 8/10 \
Soundtrack\
The soundtrack to Death Note works immensely well with what it sets itself up to be, in a similar fashion to the art style. The opening and endings to the show cannot be misinterpreted at all, since they present the themes well. I particularly think that the change in song choice between opening 1 and 2 presents the change in Light’s character throughout the show, as his psychological traits begin to change. The OST’s also used throughout certain scenes are very well done, as they add to the intense and engaging moments that occur as the show progresses. The sound to the show overall is done very well, and I don’t think it could’ve been done better. Soundtrack – 9/10\
Personal Enjoyment\
It would be a lie to say that I did not enjoy this show a lot. The tense moments between Light and L aid in engaging the reader fully, and their actions throughout the show are able to leave you amazed after you witnessed them. Though it’s evident that the later half of the show was the weaker segment, this would most definitely not take away from the enjoyment factor that you would get from the show overall. I have also seen both the sub and dub and would fully recommend either as I feel they are both very good; it's whatever you prefer with watching anime. – Personal Enjoyment – 8/10\
Overall\
Death Note is a very enjoyable show with many memorable moments that will stick with you for future time to come. It has become one of the most popular shows in the recent years and will most likely be remembered for years to come. You engage in a very compelling story with many morals that you are able to take away with you. The soundtrack holds the show justice with its intense musical compositions and the art/animation presents the morally grey tone that the story sets for itself. Though the weaker second half of the show, I still enjoyed this show very much and would fully recommend it to anyone who has yet to watch it. I am giving Death Note a 8.4/10. \
Story – 8/10\
Characters – 9/10\
Animation/Art-style – 8/10\
Soundtrack – 9/10\
Personal Enjoyment – 8/10\
Overall (calculated) - 8.4/10 \
