                          \
    Death Note is the anime that got me into watching anime. I didn't really know what to expect when I started watching it, but I was pleasantly surprised.  Although this show is great, I still think that it has several problems. Don't get me wrong, I REALLY love this show. Really. \
Story (B+): The story in Death Note starts out very fast-paced and exciting from episode one. I was sucked in right from the beginning and I always found myself wondering what was going to happen to next. There are many twists and turns that make it unique and really interesting. Unfortunately, this is\
          \
        what causes the many flaws in Death Note. The beginning is so intense that throughout the middle, it kind of seems like the author ran out of ideas and started coming up with random plot developments just to hold us over until he could think of something exciting again. The Yotsuba arc was really boring, and at times confusing, and several other parts get bogged down with too much dialogue and confusing additions to the plot. Both Light and L explain not only their own thoughts, but also eachother's. At first, this is really interesting because it's amazing how they know what the other is going to do, but eventually it becomes predictable.There's also some things that happen in the story that seem...a little too implausible (like having people in a room under surveillance for more than 50 days...wtf), but this really isn't too big of a problem.There's one MAJOR plot twist in Death Note that a lot of people have a problem with. Overall, I thought the twist was good, but after it happened the story was never able to be what it was in the beginning. The ending of Death Note should have been a climactic finale, but I found myself more dissapointed than satisfied. With all that being said, the story is still intense, and I was still very invested in it. The twists are really suspenseful and well crafted even in the very end. \
Art (A+) - The art in Death Note is some of the best. There are really no complaints here. The style of animation is distinctive, and definitely adds to the suspensful atmosphere and intense moments. Everything is done with flawless detail. The art can't be given anything less than a perfect 10. \
Sound (A+) - The same goes for sound. The music is PERFECT for this series. It goes so well with everything that happens. It really enhances moments that are emotional and intense. I was never dissatisfied with the music. The opening and ending themes are good too. Throughout the middle (I forget which episode), the opening and ending themes change. I was a little dissapointed because I really liked the first ones, but the new ones did grow on me overtime. The voice acting is really good in Death Note. Mamoru Miyano does such a good job as Light. It's definitely one of the best performances I've ever heard. All the voice actors are well suited for their part. The voice acting was another strong point of the show. \
Characters (B+) - The characters in Death Note are the same as the story - definitely a strong point, but also a major flaw. Light Yagami is one of the most memorable characters ever.  It's funny how you find yourself rooting for him even though he is clearly evil (although technically he's still the protagonist). His relationship with Ryuk  was one of the best parts of this show, but in the later episodes Light barely talks to Ryuk anymore which was really dissapointing. L was also one of my favorite characters and definitely a fan favorite. All of the Japanese police were very entertaining, and the shinigami were also funny. The characters that REALLY ruined some of the show for me were MISA and NEAR. At first, Misa is annoying, but atleast her character has a purpose (kind of) in the beginning of the show. In the later episodes, she doesn't even do anything! She ended up being a waste of space, and it was completely unnecessary to make her so dumb. Near was the other problem. He was like a less cool version of  L that magically knows everything without having to figure anything out. If they were going to copy L they might as well have just left Near out of it. The one character that I thought got the short end of the stick was Mello. He deserved wayyyy more screen time. He was one of the more intersting characters in the later episodes that actually had some depth, and he actually looked cool unlike Near. His mafia arc was alright, but I think he could have been utilized much more. The whole fight between Light and L was the driving force of the show. Taking that away and adding uninteresting characters like NEAR was really lame. The only other good character in the end was Mikami, and he wasn't even there that long. Overall, I liked the characters, but after that one big plot twist some of the new characters are kind of just...meh.  \
Enjoyment (A-) - Death Note is a very enjoyable series. When I first watched it I was sooo into it. I just couldn't stop watching. Even when the show fell short, I still enjoyed watching it a lot. It's an intense thrill ride that definitely keeps you on the edge of your seat. Although there are many intense parts, there was an extended period where I found myself pretty bored (ahem..the Yotsuba Arc), and waiting for the excitement to come back. Also, the second half of the show, while still entertaining, suffered a lot because of that big twist that happens in the middle. There's also not a lot of rewatch value because you know everything that's going to happen. I'd say after watching it twice it loses some of its appeal. Death Note is also a really well made show. I appreciate anime that are very well developed and produced when you think about all the crappy anime out there that look so cheap. Death Note definitely had a lot of effort put into it.  \
Overall (A-) - This show would have been a perfect 10, but flaws in the story and characterization keep it from achieving its full potential (in my opinion). It's definitely worth a watch for anyone who enjoys suspense, complex characters, and an in- depth story. It's sad that such a good show kind of lost its way through the middle, and was never really able to get back on track, but the creativity of the story makes up for it.  \
