      text = "                          \
    When I was about fourteen or fifteen years old, I thought Death Note was a masterpiece of brilliant writing. Now that I'm twenty-four, I look at it and realize that while its still far from the worst ever, its still completely worthy of the metric tons of mocking that it gets. And its hard to admit that because it does seem so brilliant on its face. But its time to take the red pill and face the facts: Death Note is just short of mediocre. \
The biggest picking point I have with the show is the story itself. Not the core story -- the idea\
          \
        of a single random person being granted the powers to kill anyone they want with a flick of a pen is in fact very clever -- but with its execution. Death Note is a story of conveniences that gets by on asking you to ignore the fact that when its actions are put under scrutiny, it stops making sense. Nowhere is this more prevalent than in the fact that the story gets started at all...because they're suspicious that a bunch of guys are having heart attacks and somehow conveniently link this all back to one Japanese high schooler fucking around Tokyo. Instead of staying away from the police, his guaranteed enemies, our main character Light inexplicably decides that he should buddy up with the cops so they can have a direct profile of him to attach to any crimes. We are told that he does this because he is smart (but egotistical, remember that) but to me it seems like a directly moronic action and that when you have a tool that can kill anyone indirectly that the last thing you would want is to draw attention to yourself. \
We then proceed to introduce L, possibly the most overrated character in anime history, so he can make decisions so insane that they range from being sketchy to outright violations of the Geneva Convention. But the Japanese police don't let this bug them, preferring instead to stand at the sidelines with slack jaws marveling at how smart it is that L decided to handcuff himself to a teenage who they have no evidence against. Nice. Honestly the plot just lets this character do whatever he wants, with the justification of he's smart and he's trying to catch Kira so its okay, up until he (shocker) dies. \
Instead of maybe doing something new, we proceed to just replace L with two different Ls: Near and Mello. Or, more appropriately, albino L and angry L. As haughty as I am towards these characters, I actually do like them better than L because together the pair of them have a lot more  personality than L's ceaseless 'I am smart' routine did. Near is very similar to L but has a consistent, unabated sense of humility that manifests in his near constant admittance that he cannot do the task at hand without Mello--while Mello's angry, more criminal way of attempting to solve the case through more aggressive tactics add a more fresh tone to a show that feels like its revving its wheels in the mud. I like these two and honestly their story was more engaging that Light's hissy fitting, though admittedly only to a certain extent. Near still is basically a color palette swap of L and Mello is still just batshit insane. But at least with Mello they don't try to justify the flat out unethical shit he does with 'well, he's smart'. \
I suppose that brings me to the side characters, who...honestly, what do I say about them? Only one of the members of the police force actually matters in the end. The majority of them prefer to either stand staring in slack jawed amazement at the brilliance of the main character and his three aforementioned rivals, or just directly doing whatever these four tell them to do. They are absolutely nothing short of wallpaper. The only other character worth mentioning is Misa Amane, who may as well be renamed 'Plot Device' for as much as she actually contributes to the plot. She adds another Death Note into the mix, and frankly aside from selling a shit load of porn she doesn't actually add anything to the story outside of being Light's arm candy that he doesn't even seem to like that much. And the two Shinigami just kinda float around the background after they explain how the Death Note works. Only Ryuk really has any purpose or meaning in the long run. \
Which I guess does bring me to Light himself, who I have neglected to really address so far. Like L, the story lets him get away with a lot of stupid shit on the precedent of 'you just don't get it he's really SMART'. But unlike L the character of Light is supposed to represent something akin to the idea of a false martyr and how quickly that can go south. The problem is, he doesn't ever CARE. I get it, the guy is too smart for regular life and its a strain, but this guy immediately goes full M. Bison with cheesy catchphrases and evil villain faces. The idea of a false martyr being destructive simply isn't explored, since we get only get views of the effect of Light's actions on society from television reels and occasional public shots, and Light himself never seems to be stressed by the IDEA of being a false martyr, only that he might get caught. He never really develops beyond those three ideas in his head: that he is just, that he is smart, and that he doesn't want to get caught. And I'm sorry, you don't just hand a teenager a murder device with no visible evidence trail and just leave his internal conflict at 'welp I guess I'm god now'. Light is the antithesis of writing realistic characters. \
I liked the concepts of the story. Art-wise, the show is absolutely beautiful, thick with symbolism and just gorgeous visual shots -- though unfortunately in the animation, with a show that is reliant on dialogue, this also means we end up being subject to some of the most flat out silly sequences of animation trying to look important in the history of man. Lest we never forget Light and his potato chip. Even if the story WAS as perfect as its lauded to be, that scene alone should keep anyone from rating this anime a 10. It's just silly on its face and even worse, the silliness of the animation can sometimes draw attention to the contrived nature of the story. \
It's not saying anything, its not doing anything, and Death Note is ultimately an anime that spends 37 episodes and 12 manga volumes running in place to the tune of a vague and misunderstood attempt at social commentary and human nature. It simply just is not the show, or the manga that I remembered. \
