    I was first inspired to watch Death Note because my best friend suggested it to me. When I saw how high up it was on the top anime list, it pushed me into actually watching the show and not just letting it sit in my Plan to Watch list. The anime revolves around a group of investigators searching for a mass serial killer known as Kira (AKA Light Yagami – who is the main protagonist of the anime), but little do they know that Kira is one of the investigators among them. Since I want to study criminology and justice when I go to college\
          \
        in a short few years, I was very intrigued with what this anime had in store. And so, I dove into the anime with high expectations, and believe me, I wasn’t the least bit disappointed.\
The overall story is absolutely unique and breathtaking – which is most likely the reason why it’s such a highly rated anime. The whole idea of a star-student becoming such a psychotic killer with just picking up a notebook is, well… insane! I can’t even put it into words how magnificent the storyline played out. The thought process that went through Kira and the investigators’ minds was so ingenious that I was constantly sitting in my chair, wide-eyed, thinking, \"How the HELL do they even COME UP with this sort of stuff?\" Adding onto that, the way Light was incessantly finding loopholes in the investigators’ plans to find out who Kira was had me completely flabbergasted. As an aspiring investigator, I LOVED the plot. And for those who are probably thinking it: no, Death Note didn’t inspire me to become an investigator XD. \
The art style was very clear and a pleasure to look at. I loved how they made the characters have features that made them look realistically similar to humans instead of using the traditional anime eyes and noses. It was definitely different than with what I have been watching lately, so that also kept me into the show. \
As for the music, I enjoyed it. I really liked the opening and ending theme songs. They really set the mood for the whole atmosphere of the show. I sincerely felt like the theme songs also reflected greatly with Light’s personality. Although the second theme song is indeed screamo – which I know not a lot of people are a fan of – it really shows how (excuse my language) fucked up Light is becoming with his ideals of becoming the world’s new god. And the final ending theme song that played once the show was ended fit perfectly and was a great way to calm the watcher down after all that happened in the final episode. The music that played within the anime was perfect as well. Much like the theme songs, they do justice on showing who Light is and what he is becoming due to the Death Note.\
Here we go with character development. The anime takes place over a duration of six years, so over that time, we get to see these characters grow, Especially Light, who starts off as an ordinary high school student, graduates and goes to college, and eventually ends up joining the Task Force with his father – while progressively becoming more insane along the way. It is shown magnificently how he picks up more skills when avoiding the exposure of his identity as Kira. As I previously stated, the loopholes he discovers in the investigators’ plans are amazingly intelligent, and they only continue to grow in creativity as the show progresses, and that, kept making me mutter phrases like: \"Holy mother fucking shit.\" \
My only problem with this anime was that at times things got so intense I had no idea what to do or how to comprehend what was going on. Another thing is that if you decide to watch this anime, you have to give it your full, undivided attention. Otherwise, an important fact could be missed, and believe me when I say there are a lot of important points in this anime. Other than that, watching Death Note was an amazing experience for me, and I hope it will be for you too!",
