    It really makes me happy to see a show with an interesting premise like Death Note take over the West by storm. It's something that breaks the norm and gets people to think rather than just to entertain. However the more pessimistic side of me underneath the surface makes me draw a skeptical eye towards something with a premise such as this that's actually this popular. So is it good? Despite how flawed and open ended that question is, yes. However it's a very tricky type of show to watch depending on your expectations. I went into the show and started watching it hoping to\
          \
        find an interesting gem about ethics and the implications of death. However as the show progressed it took off in a far different way with bits and pieces of the Note's philosophical implications scattered unevenly throughout. Given the fact that the initial premise was set up well enough to make both of these aspects of the show work, it's conclusion was underwhelming, and it's first and foremost a supernatural mystery thriller.\
Death Note is first and foremost a police story, not one about ethics.  It starts out as a story about a boy with a god complex and ends on the same note without much catharsis, but what's sandwiched in-between goes above and beyond the average mystery thriller. However instead of figuring out a mystery throughout the course of the show, it's all about the mental tension and conflict between the characters instead. It breaks the norm from other shows similar to it and focusing on Light trying to one-up everyone over solving the Kira killings.  This not only broke the norm but kept Light and L's mental battle interesting in the first half. Granted most of that happened through chance and internal monologues that ultimately don't uncover much, but Light and L's thought processes around the case were the most compelling part of the show, and I was surprised at how much creative power the writers put into each character. But I'll refuse to call the show a game between minds. The processes themselves are what interested me, not what plot they brought forward. While much of the plot is fun to watch much of what happens is all a little to convenient to be taken 100 percent seriously. Calling Death Note a show about mind games is like calling a lottery ticket a sodoku puzzle; it uses chances and coincidences to move the plot forward instead of taking a strand of evidence found by the characters and having the plot unfold from that. The chances and coincidences made the show interesting and compelling to watch, but the climax is just a boring game of jenga. Many of the plot devices don't lead up to a lot, and I was hoping for more answers about how the Kira killings were affecting society at large. I also wanted to know more about the Shinigami realm, because if they can put rules in the Death Note does their realm have rules too? Both were interesting aspects of the show that would have evened out all the creative brain that the show had with a little bit of message and heart.\
In terms of surface level stuff, Death Note is a very aesthetically sound show. It knows what it wants to do with it's art and sound and for the most part it does it really well. The characters designs are all creative in their own way outfit-wise and facially, and for a show that boasts quite the large cast of characters you always see more than once, this makes the aesthetic great through and through. Other shows tend to introduce more and more characters and their designs are generally carbon copies of each other or mirror characters from other shows, which make them feel like a weaker clone (for example L and Near) of the original than an entirely new character. And for a show in an urban setting where costumes and characters are more 'normal' it's noteworthy that the creators don't recycle character ideas often. The normalcy of the character design choices also makes the presence of the not-normal Shinigami even more even more jarring to the characters and the way the gods of death move the show along. They also make brilliantly mysterious and dark urban setting of the show grittier. The feel of the setting adds an extra layer of depth to the dark subject matter of the show. Even during the daytime and in the business meeting scenes there's an eerie filter over everything despite the obvious light sources.  However while the art and character design is good at reflecting the dark nature of the show, the choir singing during the action scenes was very cool but far overstayed its welcome. The music in the show isn't much to be praised, but the second intro is so good and plays reflects the chaotic nature of the second half of the show so it almost makes up for the repetitive background music.\
For the most part I really did like the characters. For me many of the background police officers and L were well defined as people. L is by far the most reasonable and fleshed out character in the show who is the most grounded in the reasons for is actions and why he's so peculiar. The fact that he doesn't get out much and is smarter than all the other characters is clearly established, makes the most sense, and makes him the most likeable character in his peculiarity. Same goes for Ryuk, he's a well defined, delightfully simple, and has a very Tim Burton quality to his character. However my problems with the characters lay in Light and Misa, as to why anyone would call either likeable is beyond me. Light in particular irritated me. He has this plan to be a god, but why? Its hard to not think of him as an angsty teen sociopath and possible Atlas Shrugged-thumper without giving him reasoning and introspection behind the more controversial killings of people who want to get in his way. It's even harder to like a character like that, let alone watch them go on said merry way for 37 episodes without some eye rolling. However the positive that both Light and L share is that they both have a full arc and are backed up by supporting and background characters that are simple, but aren't just names on paper.  The problem is that I can't say the same about major players in the second half like Mello and Near, who serve as inherent antagonists rather than interesting contributors for the story's sake. The imagery of the toys and trains did good to represent Near's childlike mind and brilliance, but like I said before there's all brain and no heart to he and Mello's rivalry. So while some of the characters are good, they don't bear full arcs that are relevant to the overarching story, and make the second half of the show significantly weaker than the first.\
While Death Note is flawed it's by no means a bad show. It could have been fleshed out far more and far exceeded with the brilliant supernatural drama that it tries to get across. The flaws of the show don't outweigh the pure originality invention engine that it is. The problem it suffers from is reaching for the cookie jar without taking the necessary steps to reach to the top of the refrigerator. Instead likes talking about how it's going to do it rather than taking the climb, but the plotting and talking sure is entertaining.\
