    [270] = {
      score = 6,
      text = "                          \
    Spoiler warning!\
*Disclaimer*\
I will sometimes refer to Light as Kira in this review since it's Light's persona.\
Ahhh...Death Note, the classic that's been seen by millions of people and the highest ranked anime on MAL's popularity list. This anime has received a lot of praise and it deserves most of it. Is it overrated? Yes, but that holds true (did i use that expression correctly? eh who cares) for literally every single anime that is considered a \"classic\". Claiming that an anime is the best anime in existance puts forth expectations that are impossible to meet. I don't know why i wrote that...ANYHOW, let's get on with\
          \
        the review :D.\
The story follows Light Yagami, a high school student with a strong sense of justice who wants to follow in his father's footsteps and become a detective. One day (by pure chance) Light comes across a notebook that belongs to a shinigami named Ryuk. Light quickly discovers that writing someone's name in the notebook while visualizing their face will cause them to die. Over the course of the series we get to witness light transform from a normal person who wants to help change the world for the better to the self proclaimed god of the new world who strikes down evildoers in an attempt to cleanse the world of filth. As you could imagine, the cops don't like it when people take matters into their own hands and so when things start to spiral out of control, they hire a world renowned detective called L who has never failed to solve a case. This is when the show evolves into a brilliant cat and mouse chase that goes back and forth between Light and L. \
The first part of Death Note is a thrilling story of clashing ideologies with so many clever twists and turns that if you haven't watched or read it, i only have one thing to say to you, WHAT ARE YOU DOING WITH YOUR LIFE?! \
Unfortunately the show takes a drastic turn for the worse when L dies (don't say that i didn't warn you). The thing that made the first part of the series such a masterpeice was the moral debate between L and Kira. All of the things that made Death Note such an interesting show just got \"washed away\" when L died. The show tries to make up for L's death by introducing Mello and Near into the show. Mello is kind of an interesting character but he barely gets any screen time and Near is literally nothing, you never hear any personality whatsoever in his thoughts like you did with L. L explained his thought process and how he came to certain conclusions but near just says stuff like \"we know ________, therefore _______\" and that's basically what Near does for his entire run. In fact, most people probably wouldn't notice if N died and was replaced with a robot. The major difference between N and L is that L has emotions (albeit very strange ones).\
Light's character also changes for the worse. In the first part of the show Light is portrayed as a man of principle with a twisted sense of justice whereas In the 2nd part of the show, he's portrayed as a complete douchebag without any morals whatsoever. \
At least the conclusion of the show was handled pretty well. Light got what he deserved and everyone lived happily ever after...nah.\
Even though the 2nd part of the show is kinda mediocre, Death Note is still worth watching and i can understand why some people think it's the best anime of all time.\
