    [475] = {
      score = 7,
      text = "                          \
    Death Note Review:\
Hey guys!  So this is my review of Death Note, one of the most popular anime titles of all time.  Before I begin I will first say that this is a noteworthy starter kit anime for anyone showing interest in the genre.  In my view, Death Note plays as a great stepping stone for those interested in crime investigation themed shows, as well as the genre of anime as a whole.  For me personally, Death Note was not my starter kit anime staple, however, I myself have forwarded it to many of my friends, and they’ve instantly become addicted.\
          \
         I feel that as an anime fan it is important to have these types of shows, and without titles like Death Note, the anime community would not have as big of a following.  Nonetheless, I would like to give Death Note a good review of all of its pros and cons, and most certainly point out the many flaws this show has.  Although Death Note is a favorite amongst the anime community, I would also like to prove a point that this anime is not as good as people actually think it is.  By me basically saying this anime is in fact overrated, I will also say that Death Note does bring entertainment in many forms through its story and character development, and can also leave the viewer on the edge of their seat throughout the 37 episodes it offers.\
Story 8/10:  To provide just the basics of the story, a high schooler named Light Yagami picks up a journal with mystical powers.  By using this journal (aka the Death Note) he can write someone’s name in the journal and they will die.  To put simply, the story develops into an investigation and the best detective in the world, named L, is assigned to the case to put a stop to the powers of the Death Note.  It is essentially like Sherlock Holmes being assigned to the most unusual type of investigation, and prior to this particular assignment, \"L\" has never failed in solving an investigation.  To end this brief synopsis, I will say that this story progression is very fluid and easy to follow.  By episode 1 or 2 you will more than likely be hooked into watching the rest of the series to see what happens.  To my prior point of saying that this is a great starter kit anime, the first 12 episodes should be enough to prove why.  The various situations involving the Death Note and the investigators have the story being turned on it’s head on numerous occasions, and a lot of times will have you in shock at what the hell happened.  Cliffhangers toward the end of episodes are initiated on a regular basis, along with unexpected twists in the story, especially with the main character Light.  As a person who has already seen the show, it is easy to analyze the story progression and the ethics behind having the Death Note.  This anime really makes you analyze the main character Light in his current situation, and makes you ponder about a scenario where if you had the journal what would you do with it?  Through its 2 arcs in the story line, the progression is easy to monitor and maintains consistency throughout the show, which is why I believe its story line is solid.  \
Art 7/10:  The art in this show is a little darker than what I am normally used to in the typical animes’ I usually watch.  By no means is anything pretty or outstanding in this anime in terms of its artwork.  The art really does however have a positive effect on the show as a whole, in terms of having a dark contrast; considering the show itself can be pretty obscure.  I can’t necessarily criticize the artwork in this anime, since it particularly suits the show well, yet It does take some getting used too if you’re unaware of the dark types of animes that are out there.   Not too many complaints from my end on this category.\
Sound 6/10: How can I describe the sound in this anime.  If I could put it in two words, \"incredibly average,\" would seem to fit the description.  Although the investigation and crime solving scenes throughout the show are very good, I will mostly complain about Death Note’s intros and ending for this show.   Like most of my reviews, I remain consistent on the notion that I love my anime intros and endings.  They get me ready for the show, and Death Note is probably the worst show I have ever seen in terms of music.   Literally, all intros and all endings are terrible.  I never once felt relaxed, interested, or even excited to watch this show from its intros, nor was I satisfied with the ending compositions.  To be honest, the one intro to Death Note around the 28 episode mark is death metal sounding, which you would think fit right into the transition of the show starting; sure enough it really made me feel like my ears would start bleeding.  Personally, the beginnings and endings to Death Note were not my favorite; luckily, the 20ish minutes outside the intros and endings  to the story arcs did a good job with the audio, and made the case study of the death note have an eerie feel to it.  I would say overall, that the sound to this show is average at best, although it does a decent job of keeping a good vibe throughout the investigation.\
Character 8/10:  The characters in Death Note, like in many anime, are what make it a solid show.  I think I can speak for everyone when I say this, characters can make or break the story and overall interest towards a show.  That is especially true for Death Note.  The first story arc focuses particularly on Light, Reyuk (The Shinygami), and the internal investigators including \"L\".  There are many outside actors of course like Lights family and other agents that I won’t mention because it will spoil the enjoyment.  Anyway, the first story arc of Death Note, and the character development is pretty awesome.  Although I hate Light Yagami as a character for ethical and moral reasons (which you will discover), I will praise the writers for really thinking outside the box in terms of what the characters would look like, and how they would be perceived by the viewer (Especially L).  You’ll laugh when you finally meet L, because it isn’t anything you would expect a master investigator to look like, which of course makes it all the more entertaining.  The show in my eye really tethered off after a few episodes in the second story arc of the show.  At the time when I was watching, I grew bored at times and I felt I wasn’t as motivated to watch the second arc as I was the first.  Fortunately, I did finish the show and am currently watching it a second time now, and quite truthfully more engaged in what is happening to the characters.  Ultimately, the characters in this show are portrayed well by the writers, and if you’re going to give the show the credit it deserves, it is easy to pick this category as its strongest selling point.  \
Enjoyment 7/10:  Like I said above, I enjoyed Death Note’s first story arc moreso than its second story arc, which is mostly why I am giving this category a lower rating.  As much as I enjoyed the first story arc, which I would likely give an 8.5/9 out of 10, the rest of the shows build up I believe lacked particular flare to it than its earlier episodes.  Nonetheless, I still managed to enjoy the show beginning to end, and although it was tough for me to power through the second arc, I gained a more appreciative attitude towards the show once I finished.  \
Overall 7/10:  With overall ratings and Death Note’s quality in mind, I would like to be a little more specific instead of a general rating of a 7, but on my own rating scale put this anime at a 7.7 ish.  The overall show is fantastic for anyone in the works of becoming an anime fan, and is a perfect start to the shows the genre provides.  To me, this is not a personal favorite of mine, however it does just enough for me to maintain a respectful appreciation for it.  My gratitude for it quite specifically stems from the fact that it remains one of the household anime titles today, and it serves as a starting line for those who have the desire to watch the many phenomenal shows the anime genre provides.  As I repeat myself, this is a great show to inform your friends, and even family about (I even had my Mom watch it lol).  This show is what they call a gateway drug/anime to shoot you off into the fray of many other prestigious titles.  Without series like Death Note, followers can’t gain interest into newer animes’ that become released, which is why I like to label it as a starter kit anime.  You can add this anime as well as Full Metal Alchemist as the big shows to make sure to watch, because they will elevate you into titles you may or may not have heard before.  Hopefully you give Death Note a shot, and like I said in my review of Code Geass, this is a bucket list show even if you’re not an anime fan.   All in all, this is a good show, and although I believe the community overblows its quality, it is definitely a show worth talking about.     \
",
