    [664] = {
      score = 6,
      text = "                          \
    Here it is. The infamous anime by the name of Death Note that took the anime world by storm in fall 2006. Studio Madhouse was not pumping out 2-3 anime a season anymore and went back to their ways that made the Studio such a powerhouse a few years prior. The director chosen for the role was an ambitious story board guy by the name of Tetsurou Araki whom later went on to direct some other hits like Attack on Titan and Guilty Crown. Death Note is a different anime to say the least and in the psychological thriller genre which focuses on plot rather\
          \
        than the characters.\
Motivation and plot are rather simple. A Shinigami/death god was bored and \"lost\" his notebook. A young man named Light finds the notebook and learns that if you write someone’s name in it as long as you know their face would die. Light then begins his quest to cleans the world of evil using this book as well as remaining secretive from a detective named ‘L’ and his crew who are hot on his trail to capture him.\
This plot is rather interesting and thrilling, but what makes Death Note so enticing are the characters. L is the most interesting as his personality is beyond a simple explanation. The eccentric cat and mouse game that Light and L play make the first arc of the story one of the best ever in anime. One issue though after the initial arc, the second tends to repeat scenarios from the first going from Light using the death note in an interesting way, followed by L finding some invisible clue, and Light somehow arbitrarily escaping, thus continuing the cycle. Finally, once certain events happen and a time skip occurs, this is where the plot falls straight off of a cliff. A few more characters are introduced each contributing greatly to the arc they are part of, but fails to even come close to the thrilling tales and moments of that original arc. So much of the plot drags and the viewer loses that sense of caring why events occur. \
Sure, the animation and art quality is top notch. The music more or less fits the show, but more often than not over dramatizes moments creating an unintentional comedic relief. Voice acting in both English and Japanese are fantastic, so picking either or is a hit.\
Summing up Death Note could be best stated as a series that went to 37 episodes that when the second arc concluded end at episode 25 would have made for an almost perfect show with only a few flaws. Instead, a third arc was made to continue the story (as did the manga with rumors ensuing) that ultimately kills the show. Such a shame for such an iconic anime.\
        ",
      helpful = 1,
    },
