    [745] = {
      score = 8,
      text = "\
                          \
    (Originally Written: December 2009)\
---------------------------------------\
***WARNING - SPOILERS!!!***\
---------------------------------------\
Hello everybody! This is my review of the anime series Death Note. Once again, you are welcome to add your own thoughts to this, as long as they are suitable! Please take note of the SPOILER WARNING above though!\
Well, what can I say. Since Wednesday 4th November 2009 until Sunday 20th December 2009, I do believe I may have been watching one of the all-time greatest animes ever written.\
Literally, almost everything about the series including characters and their personalities, along with the whole storyline and the way everything panned out was near perfect.\
But overall, there is not an anime I\
          \
        have yet seen that can even be compared to Death Note in the same sense of the amount of effort that was put into making everything about the characters pan out just perfectly.\
Nobody was ever predictable, a hard feat to achieve indeed. And also the creators forced the viewer/reader to choose a side, Light or 'L'. Personally, I fell immediately on the side of Light, however, this was probably intended, mainly due to the fact that L doesn't enter the story line till episode 2 and doesn't come into his prime until a few episodes later.\
This gives the viewer/reader a chance to build up a strong liking of Light. Hence, they develop a natural dislike to L when he first appears, as he appears to want to put a stop to Light's actions.\
However, as time passes, I found myself becoming ever more interested in the way that L put across his methods of thinking. Most of his assumptions would likely be classed as mad guesses in the real world, however, seeing as this is based on a story, the characters believe him.\
Another point is the way that for every single brilliant plan or idea that Light comes up with, L always seems to find a way to overcome it. However, the fact that this also happens in reverse. keeps the story in a well-maintained balance.\
Personally, I thought that the idea that Light had everything planned up to the moment that he and L, now working together, managed to retrive the Death Note from Higuchi, was incredible in that it was so hard and yet so easy to believe he would've done it.\
Then when Rem sacrificed herself to kill Watari and 'L', it came as a big shock as even I had not been expecting it to happen, and also not so suddenly. I believe this element of suprise is a key factor which is upheld throughout the series in order to maintain the audience's focus.\
From then on, knowing that any conventional anime has only 13-26 episodes, once I found out that there was 39 episodes (38 & 39 being OVAs) I realised that the anime was far from over with another 12 episodes left.\
When the USA got involved I felt kind of annoyed as it appeared that they were interfering with everything in the storyline. Eventually, I came to see that the way that Near thought and acted was meant to make you think that he was a kind of 'Son of L' so to speak.\
He was meant to give the impression that even though the real L is dead, there's remains a feeling such as his spirit is still present in order to seek revenge upon Light, using Near as his medium.\
And so another epic battle of wits insued until Episode 36 when they finally met: Light and Near.\
At this point I felt almost certain that Light's plan was going to working, what with the USA tampering witht the wrong Death Note and Mikami Teru having the real Death Note.\
How shocked/annoyed/confused I was to find out that Near had thought of this and also altered the real Death Note, and exposing Light undeniable as Kira.\
When Light pulled the tiny piece of the Death Note out of his watch, I felt that there would be a sort of 'Romeo and Juliet' type scenario, where Light would write Near's name on the Death Note, killing him and also be killed by both his and Near's associates.\
Unfortunately, Matsuda was too quick for him and managed to shoot Light's hand, stopping him from writing, then shooting him several times when he tried to do it again.\
I felt incredibly shocked that after all that had happened, all of Light's efforts to make what he thought would be a genuinely good new world, were all in vein.\
It was also quite sad to see him die at the end, knowing all that he had accomplished had been dashed in one fell swoop. And that also, he was eventually killed not just by the people he had been working with, but by the man seemingly the least likely to be able to accomplish such an act.\
So, overall a very well constructed anime.\
I have only one slightly negative point for this. Death Note appeared to suffer the same problem as Trigun, in that it rather dragged itself out slowly, but it was made up for by the multiple key points and developments that linked each episode.\
        ",
